This was not the first time that this had happened and it's why I now have to spend A LOT OF TIME in my design process figuring out what questions I actually need answers to in order to progress the piece. Otherwise, I will get sidetracked.

In my brain I knew that the thumbnails were an important part of the process! But I'd gotten confused as to what info I needed to do them and so I'd accidentally lasered in on the questions I was more confident in knowing how to answer and...well, I'd lost sight of thumbnails.

Case in point- me presenting a sketchbook full of lovely character designs and setting research and location designs to my tutor two weeks before hand-in, and my tutor pointing out that was all very nice but I hadn't actually done any thumbnails of the pieces I was going to make. https://t.co/Y2gIcixyx9

That means my brain ends up focusing on answering questions it knows how to, even if those answers are ultimately useless in the grand scheme of figuring out the drawing. I'll end up with a bunch of research work and drawings that don't actually help me at all.

I always wondered why even when I am very aware of the necessary process for a drawing, especially in the development stage of a piece, I always end up focusing on stuff that is ultimately useless. It's because my brain is trying to focus on what it feels most equipped to tackle!

@Timberoo_ Fast fashion is one I always come back to because it's such a great illustration of how unethical companies can use poverty to force a monopoly on a product that is damn near impossible to break once you're stuck in it.

@Timberoo_ I think it's a genuinely useful phrase when we're talking about the monopoly of certain facets of life by unethical companies we have no choice but to use, but it's way too often used as a catch all to mean "I chose to support a terrible company and I refuse to feel bad about it"

"No ethical consumption under capitalism" isn't an excuse to overconsume things that aren't necessary to our life and wellbeing. Media and culture *are* vital to our life and wellbeing, but we can always be more conscientious of the methods and amount of consumption.

Just. Please. Stop being shocked that Disney has the money and power to shape the political landscape however it wants when the moment they release a new Star War or Marvel show or film you all lose your heads and rush to give them exactly what they need- money and power.

If you really, really want to watch it, pirate it. PIRATE IT. The creative team has already been paid (maybe not well, but that's a different conversation) so you're just lining Disney's pockets and enabling their horrendous business practices and overreach.

Sometimes you have to use Amazon to order stuff you absolutely need even if you're being deliberate and thoughtful about your consumption because they have monopolised access to certain products in certain regions. You don't need to watch the next Disney film/TV series to live.

"no ethical consumption under capitalism" means we have little choice in the provision of certain goods and services necessary for everyday life even if we disagree with the company's morals, not that you can give money to Disney and not feel bad

I'd had that moment of "but I do that?" when the same friend had been telling me about their experiences of symptoms before, but the combo of having to suddenly manage all my time AND get back into work after a break made me realise that I wasn't experiencing time normally.

Time loss. I got back from holiday in 2019 and just lost two weeks. Couldn't have told you what I was doing, only that I'd fully intended to do *something* and just somehow...hadn't. It was a friend telling me about their experiences with the same that finally made it click. https://t.co/IQD0h1PUCY

So figuring out I was neurodiverse made it much easier for me to properly attribute my struggling to my ADHD, not to any moral failing in myself. And that makes it much easier to ask for help, which means those tasks actually get done regularly and I don't feel like shit!

Like many girls, I was socialised to expect and bear the burden of organising and running a household, and to feel very deep and intense shame if any part of it fell short. Even when you know that's bullshit, it's still hard to unlearn what you've seen and known all your life.

Asking my partner to take care of tasks I find particularly difficult. I'm terrible at tasks with multiple stages, especially when there's a long period of time between each stage. So my partner now organises those tasks, and it works much better! https://t.co/2JfnIhNQzI

@CobbleSprite Licensing and stock art are super budget friendly ways to support artists! I love licensing out pieces where I can and it's way more affordable for creators than commissions! 💖

I know we're all out here just doing our best. But artists so often get shafted by poor flat fees and predatory industry standards and I need game creators to be more conscientious of exactly what they're asking of us when we're asked to price up for work there's no budget for.

You're investing in their ability to be around to illustrate your next game. You're investing in their ability to still be making art for tabletop in several years time. I want tabletop to be an industry where we all work together to make sure we can all keep making games.

I've said it before and I'll say it again- custom art is an investment. An expensive investment. You do not have to have it for your game to be lovely. But you're not just investing in art- you're investing in the artist. You're investing in a relationship with them.

Paying an artist properly and fairly for one standout piece for your book, making sure that they can live and keep working, and padding out the rest with licensed pieces or stock art or public domain images is a wonderful and viable option for indie TTRPGs.

Please, if it feels like artists are overcharging- they're not. We're trying to survive over here. If you want us to be able to keep making art for your games you have to pay us a living wage. That is expensive, yes. But we cannot keep working unpaid hours and we shouldn't.

I understand that it feels like your game has to have lots of pretty custom art to compete with the big dogs. But if you're not paying your artists fairly you are creating an environment where it is impossible for artists to make a living, and we have to quit.

It's really tiring. I don't know how much I can do about it other than saying, yet again, that if you want to commission artists for your game it is up to YOU to make sure you have adequate budget to do so. I can't tell you how to get that money but please don't underpay artists.

And the thing is, for most artists, we're not getting residuals. We get paid a flat fee for our work, so if we are forced to undercut ourselves to get work, we never get that money back. We are working at a loss, all the time.

It is almost impossible to price art fairly in the TTRPG space. There is so little money in the development of games that either you undercut yourself and have to do a whole bunch of work essentially for free, or you have to not be a TTRPG artist primarily.

@KatCardy Managing housekeeping with ADHD is not necessarily about finding ways to force yourself to do tasks that feel tedious and unnecessary and will never be anything but. It's as much about finding ways to not HAVE to do those tasks. Make the tasks obsolete wherever you can!!!

@KatCardy And I think once you've grasped that function over form mentality that is key to creating an ADHD friendly house, once you've realised that we literally do not have the brain space to keep a conventionally 'neat' house, it's open season on all the tasks you HATE doing.

@KatCardy It literally made me stop and have to take five minutes because it's the perfect function over form solution, and I'd never had someone validate that a lot of these tasks just. Don't need to exist? That finding ways to NOT do the tasks was a solid solution? It blew my mind.

@KatCardy Basically, if you have trouble finding the executive function to match and roll all your socks, get rid of all your socks. Buy several pairs of the same sock in two different neutral colours. Bung them all in your sock drawer. You now never need to match socks ever again.

Sometimes you've just got to trust that the river of your process, of your development, is taking you somewhere beautiful. Even if it winds and curves, even if there are moments you're not sure why you're swimming in it, no river ends where it started. It can't.

Every time I see these, even though they're half a decade old (oh god) and they don't stand up to my work now, I remember how important they were in making me realise that things were going to be alright, even if my work was changing, even if I didn't know where I was going.

And in the end...it did make me happy. I didn't make the best response to the brief, or the most technically sound artwork, or even the best artwork I think I could have made. But I made the artwork that I needed to make- the work that made me feel like it was going to be okay.

I honestly barely ended up considering the brief. I just wanted to know if this new direction made me happy, if it put the fire of creating back in my veins. I was not in a good place and I just wanted to feel something positive again. I was thinking, seriously, of quitting.

It felt like my work was a river and I was fighting the current, trying desperately to get back to where I was before, exhausting myself. This project was, in a lot of ways, me taking a deep breath and letting the process wash me with it. No way back upstream.

Save your entry money, put it towards buying your own marketing or buying stock or going to some sort of event. Something you are guaranteed to see a return on instead of throwing money at a competition you are extremely unlikely to see anything from. Fuck art competitions.

They'll run a big spiel about how the entry fees help pay for the prizes but a lot of the prizes are offered through partner companies and actually cost the host company nothing to give out, despite them making a big deal about its 'value'. Most of that money goes elsewhere.

Pay-per-entry competitions lock out poorer working class and early career artists in favour of rich artists who can afford to pay for as many entries as they like. It lines the pockets of the company running the competition while offering very little in terms of prize.

I see 'Illustration Awards' season is here again so here's your reminder that any competition requiring you to pay for entry is a scam, no matter how high profile the company running it is *cough cough AOI cough*.

@sethsmithart Sugar and processed carbs are two foods that can trigger dopamine production, so the ADHD brain is more likely to crave those kinds of foods for a quick dopamine hit. We also have issues with our brains and bodies communicating hunger signals which can lead to overeating.

If you're interested in reading about current corpse law I'd recommend reading A Grave Offence: Corpse Desecration and the Criminal Law by S I Jones and A Corpse in Law by Andrew Campbell-Tiech. Both very good papers.

@killswitchkatie It's actually older and weirder- in the 1600s someone misinterpreted "corpses can't have property" as "corpses can't *be* property" and corpse law has worked on the basis of nobody having legal right to a corpse ever since!

@beemure You'd be charged with unlawful disinterment, yep! Can't disinter without permission from either the Church of England on consecrated ground or the Department of Justice in most other circumstances.
Anyway, this is a fascinating rabbit hole and I'll be interested to see how today's sentencing potentially brings corpse law into the forefront again.

So you can steal a corpse and that's not punishable by current law- nobody owns it, so you haven't stolen it from anyone. But you can't steal an anatomical specimen that's been preserved. That's not a corpse- that's property.

There's also a fascinating intersection where corpses obtain legal value through skilled labour- anatomical specimens aren't seen as 'corpses' but as 'pieces of art' because they've been transformed for new purposes through the application of artistic and medical skill.
@missgaley I'd imagine Canada has more stringent laws, given its proximity to the US. But yeah, I was pretty shocked to find out just how lax UK law is about corpses!

It's fascinating that our country, which is and historically has been so preoccupied with death, the dead, and the 'proper' observance of burial and mourning, does not recognise a corpse as having much legal standing at all.

You can be charged for necrophilia (only came into law in 2003), and you can be charged with preventing a burial, and you can be charged with holding human tissue without a license or consent, but that's basically it when it comes to corpse law.

The David Fuller case has brought up something that I was talking to my partner about just the other week- the UK does not have abuse of a corpse laws. You can't be arrested for desecration of a corpse the way you can be in the US. There are very few corpse protection laws.

There aren't a whole lot of photos of it. It wasn't an important building at all, really. But I'm glad it was there to inspire me. I'm glad I got to see something beautiful in the long, drawn out end of a building nobody else really noticed.

And maybe it wasn't as big as I remember. Maybe it wasn't as lovely. Maybe it was just a dilapidated old building that had passed its use and was better off as rubble. But the strange, aching, lonely feeling I remember it inspiring in me is what I chase in all my drawings.

Most of the people who remember it probably remember it when it was open and serving the village as a community hub that was loved and lively. But I only remember it desolate and empty and slowly falling apart and it was *beautiful*, even at a distance.

It's strange to me that to other people it was just this weird old building that they never thought about once it had been demolished, and to me it sparked a lifelong appreciation of the beauty of abandoned buildings and I've never stopped thinking about it for the last 15 years.

Well I just figured out it was real!!! It was the old miners institute and it was abandoned since about 1994, so about 10 years out of use when I first laid eyes on it. It was pretty big, and I imagine it must have been quite difficult to find the funds to maintain it.

It was demolished when I was about 9 or 10, at a guess. Many years later I asked people what it was, but nobody I asked could ever remember it. I genuinely thought maybe I'd just created some sort of false memory? Like I'd just imagined this weird building nobody else remembered?

For years I've been trying to remember a very distinctive abandoned building that was in the next village over from where I grew up. I remembered it being huge and beautiful to me as a child, something I always saw from the road but never up close. It was magnificent and sad.

And when the jealousy doesn't take up my whole emotional brain space because I'm panicking and feeling bad about it, there's space for the feelings I do want to express others. Pride, joy, excitement. Those are much more useful for my friend. The jealousy is useful for me.

I tend to find that once I've actually acknowledged the jealousy, and promised myself that I will spend time with it later to find ways to fulfil the need it is trying to show me, it feels much, much less dominating. Still there, sure, but no longer taking up all my emotion.

If you find yourself feeling jealous about someone else's accomplishments, take a deep breath. Give yourself a moment to acknowledge the jealousy, and set yourself time later, alone, to work through it. Then box it up and put it aside. It's not useful now, but it will be later.

Jealousy is just your brain's way of telling you that some part of yourself feels unfulfilled- that there is a need that isn't being met. Part of processing jealousy in a healthy and productive way is figuring out what that need might be, and how you can make steps towards it.

I think feeling jealous when someone else, even someone you love dearly, has something you want is entirely normal. The world has a lot of narratives about 'selfish' feelings and 'bad' feelings and that's not true. Your feelings are neutral, but your response to them is not.

This isn't to say that jealousy makes you a bad person- but don't let jealousy dictate your response to the success of others. Jealousy is to process in your own time, and it's a useful feeling for figuring out what you want to achieve. But never make it someone else's problem. https://t.co/oQBqkbwgxp

Maybe one day I'll buy an Eversharp Square 4" pencil just to see what it's like to use. But I don't think it'll replace my trusted Staedtler Mars clutch pencil, mostly because I can't afford to buy vintage lead all the time. I'll stick to round leads, I think.

You never really think about innovations in things like pens and pencils. We use them all the time and just assume they were always the best they could be. But I'm a nerd and think stationery development, especially early iterations of stuff we take for granted now, is cool.

You get specialised pencils with specialised lead shapes that just become obsolete through the advance of technology, like lofting pencils with wide, flat leads, and then you get some leads that were made just to see if there was a better way of doing things.

Unusual leads and pencils are so fascinating, because imagine the alternate timeline where these square leads worked as intended and became the adopted lead shape for mechanical pencils. It's a small thing that might have made a big impact on the way these tools developed.

There's a lot of documentation about the Eversharp brand in the USA, but almost nothing about its manufacture in the UK. The Square 4” leads were no longer being manufactured by the early 40s, it seems, replaced with standard circular leads, some of which I also have! https://t.co/NbNPxg3Ou3

I mean, sort of square. Square with rounded corners. The lead was patented by Robert Back in 1932 and the idea was that square leads would fit into more pencils and also jam less. Cool concept! Never really worked properly. Corners shaving off in the pencil caused more jams. https://t.co/Lj18XEeA9k

Thank you to everyone who hired me over the last year, you've been amazing and I've loved all our work.  Thank you again to my friends who have loved and supported me, you know who you are and I adore every single one of you. Here's to an excellent year 4! https://t.co/rpr2nGScYw

I think this next year of freelancing is going to be about directing this new focus into growing parts of my business that have, admittedly, gotten a little lost in the mess. But that's okay! It's been a weird time and now I'm ready to start moving things along.

This year has been both strange and thrilling. I've essentially had to relearn how to do my job but it's paying off. I feel less anxious, more productive, and more hopeful. Last year felt pretty bleak, so it's been nice to feel like no, actually, I can do this. https://t.co/AGzKWtdzQP

So, for 2022:
- Up my prices.
- Start gunning for bigger client projects.
- Regular weekly streams.
- A new personal project creating regular content for Patreon/a new subscription.
- A structured approach to balancing personal and client work. 

I think those are good goals!

It's a project that revolves in part around travel and exploration, and that's part that I'm really looking forward to. I'm going to work really hard to make it a success and I want it to become something that makes up a good chunk of my work and income. I think you'll like it.
@MattHTaylor Girlboss Gatekeep the presidency

My plan is to finish the planning stage by the end of the year, and then start setting up the structure for it to become a regular thing that I work on. I plan to reformat either my Patreon or a new website subscription around it, which will help me update regularly.

I'm also currently working on planning for a large personal project that I'm really, really excited about. I've realised that the best way for me to make regular personal work is within the scope of a self set project, like my Folklore Thursday pieces. It keeps me on track.

Some other plans for this upcoming year- I want to start streaming regularly again! I've missed it, and I want it to be part of my weekly schedule. I fell off hard because I've had little time to spend on personal work this year, but my goal is to make time for streams each week.

That may mean I have to take a look at my marketing strategies and really knuckle down on finding bigger projects, but I think that's achievable. I've just got to put the time and effort into it and I want to find resources that'll help me do that.

Something I have realised I need to do for this coming year is up my prices. If I feel very busy but I'm still stressed about money, then I'm not charging enough. That's on me- I've got to advocate for myself and be confident that my work is worth a good wage.

And I've gotten to work on some really, really cool stuff! The highlight of my year was getting to work with Wyrmwood on their tarot deck. They've been a dream client for me for a while and I wasn't expecting that to happen so soon. It was really exciting, and I'm thankful. 💖 https://t.co/deoICAv9CW

In terms of work, being able to keep focus more consistently has meant that this year has felt far more stable with work coming in. I don't feel like there's been much time this year where I haven't had anything on my plate, which has been a really nice feeling. https://t.co/ZEXtY9QQtZ

Ultimately, I feel like I have a good enough grasp of what life feels like now to start planning for the future and restructuring things to give myself more time and focus on the things I want to achieve, and that's really, really exciting. I feel ready to tackle that work.

A lot of this year has just been giving myself space to figure out what life looks like without a brain full of bees. What does work look like? What does home look like? What is too much? What am I still struggling with? How does this change my process? I've had to relearn a lot.

Getting onto medication has been life changing, seriously. It turns out that when someone switches off all the radio static in your head, it's a lot easier to think and do and plan. While there are still days my focus is worse, meds have made me consistently more able to work.

Having words to describe my experiences and re-evaluating my struggles with that context has given me perspective on myself that I wasn't ever really sure I'd get. I've found it so much easier to be kind to myself knowing that there is a reason my brain does what it does.

So let's start off with the first thing that happened, that impacted the whole rest of my year (in a good way)- at the beginning of 2021, after 15 months of waiting for an assessment, I got diagnosed with Inattentive ADHD. It's not exaggerating to say it's changed everything.

Year 2 of freelancing was pretty god damn rough, what with a global panini and Brexit and the economy crashing and not knowing how long any of that would last. It was definitely a long night of the soul year for me. Lots of stress and panic and wondering if I needed to quit art.

Three years! It's time again for our yearly State of the Morrighan, where I look back on the year I've had and wonder what on earth is happening to this world we live in. And also maybe tell you a bit about my plans for the next year! https://t.co/vMI8C3Zp5p https://t.co/jEgR6jU05M

@NatasaIlincic Yep! 5000K lighting produces a slightly cooler blue but very bright light. You also want to look for a bulb with a high CRI (Colour Rendering Index)- the higher the number, the closer any colours will appear to how they would be under natural daylight.

@cstampeen Death date also doesn't help much, since most death record details are only available on request and are generally only searchable by the quarter in which the death was registered, not the actual death date itself. So dead leads on both ends.

@cstampeen I've tried, but unfortunately pre-1837 birth records are all kept in parish records, which would mean having to know where he was born in order to find them. Census also doesn't give exact birth dates, only ages, which means you only ever get an estimated birth year from them.

Some day we will all be a confusing jumble of unintelligible data disconnected from any actual remnants of our lives and unable to ever be reconciled into a whole person, which really puts things into perspective
This sort of weird existentialism about the fleeting nature of context is why I like collecting dead people's stuff.

In 100 years will someone be frantically searching through the BMD database for you, trying to figure out how you existed, trying to untangle you from all the other people who share your name and were born in your hometown? Will they succeed? Will you ever be known again?

It's interesting to think about lost context. If in a hundred years all your photos got shown to someone who had no idea who you were, how much would they be able to find out about your life from those photos alone? Or just from a single photo?

Frustrating, but the person who wrote those details on the photo never imagined that 130 years later I'd be fishing that photo out of a box at some junk shop or antiques fair. They thought that their descendants would keep the photo and the context would be passed down.

And I feel like with an exact birth and death date, finding this man in the records should be easier!!! But his birth predates centralised birth records and death records can be extremely vague and are usually grouped only by quarter! So I can't find him!!

The most frustrating photo I own in that regard is this distinguished gentleman, whose friends or family helpfully wrote on his exact date of birth and death, but unhelpfully excluded all other details. https://t.co/7QPxDFxQzF

Sometimes I find photographs with really tantalising slivers of identifying info on them! Names! Dates!! But unless the stars align it's very hard to say for sure which records are the correct ones, and so I can never pinpoint with any certainty who these people actually were.

Sometimes I think about all entirely unidentifiable photographs of people out there in the world, hundreds of thousands of lives that were so carefully documented by loved ones and friends, just entirely served from that context

And then I go buy them.
